    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
      <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="Aink422-kilavi">mīḷkiṉṟāṉ tērppākaṉ kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">He who is returning spoke [this] so that the charioteer heard.</p>
            </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <lg xml:id="Aink422">        
            <l>kaṭumpari neṭuntērk kālval puravi</l>
                <l>neṭuṅkoṭi mullaiyoṭu taḷavamala rutira</l>
                <l>viraiyupu kaṭaiināñ celli</l>
                <l>ṉiraivaḷai muṉkai varuntalō vilaḷē.</l>
          </lg>
          <lg xml:lang="en">
            <l>So that the blossoms of the golden jasmine and the long creeper-jasmine drop,</l>
            <l>if we go, quickly driving the strong-legged horses of the switly moving chariot,</l>
            <l>the one with rows of bangles on her her arms</l>
            <l>-- she will not suffer at all.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">I follow Wilden's interpretation of this syntactic formation -- vebal noun in -<foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">al-ō</foreign> + the negative root <foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">il</foreign>- (in this case, <q xml:lang="ta-Latn"><hi rend="italic">varuntalō ilaḷē</hi></q>). The -<foreign xml:lang="ta-Latn">ō</foreign> particle seems to function as a focaliser, marking and emphasising the topic: 'as for x...' (cf. KT 292.9, NA 150.11, AN 186.17).</note></l></lg>
        </div>
      </body>
    </text>
